    "title": "AI & Robotics Snacks — April 20, 2026",
    "date": "2026-04-20",
    "tags": ["ChatGPT outage", "Beijing robot marathon", "Google Gemma 4", "Maine data center ban", "OpenAI Cerebras deal"],
    "fresh": true,
    "content": "**AI & Robotics Snacks** — April 20, 2026\n\n---\n\n## 🔴 ChatGPT Went Down on a Sunday Morning. The Internet Noticed.\n\nOpenAI experienced a partial outage on April 20 affecting conversations, voice mode, image generation, and login — for at least 90 minutes starting around 10:05 AM ET. The company said it was \"monitoring the recovery.\"\n\n- **What broke:** Multi-service disruption covering core chat, voice, image generation, and authentication. The timing — Sunday morning — caught millions of weekend users mid-conversation.\n- **The context:** ChatGPT processes hundreds of millions of queries per week. When it goes down, it's no longer a niche tech incident — it's infrastructure news.\n\n*\"Monitoring the recovery\" is the most diplomatic way to say \"we're not sure when it comes back.\"*\n\n**Sources:** [TechRadar](https://www.techradar.com/news/live/chatgpt-down-april-2026)\n\n---\n\n## 🤖 Robots Ran a Half-Marathon in Beijing. Some Finished.\n\nOn April 19, Beijing's Yizhuang zone hosted a humanoid robot half-marathon demonstrating major gains in speed, stability, and autonomous navigation compared to the previous year.\n\n- **The progress:** Last year's robots mostly stumbled. This year they ran — not quickly, but continuously, with improved stability and real-time obstacle navigation.\n- **The signal:** China is treating humanoid robotics as a national showcase. Running a half-marathon is not a product milestone — it's a diplomatic flex. The robots are the message.\n\n*Half-marathon in Beijing. The robots didn't win. But they finished.*\n\n**Sources:** [DigiTimes](https://www.digitimes.com/news/a20260420PD214/china-humanoid-robot-robotics-development-2026.html)\n\n---\n\n## 💻 Gemma 4 Is Four Models: E2B, E4B, 26B MoE, 31B Dense — All Open Source\n\nGoogle's Gemma 4 (released April 2) isn't one model — it's four, from a 2B that runs on a phone to a 31B dense that scored 89.2% on AIME 2026 math. The previous generation scored 20.8%. Apache 2.0. Runs on a single H100.\n\n- **The lineup:** E2B/E4B (128K context, down to Raspberry Pi); the 26B MoE activates only 4B parameters per token — 97% of the 31B's quality at 8x less compute; the 31B Dense hits 84.3% on GPQA Diamond, beating Llama 4 Scout's 74.3%.\n- **The math jump:** 20.8% → 89.2% on AIME 2026 in one generation. That's not incremental progress — that's a different category of model.\n\n*Google open-sourced a model that beats Llama 4 on graduate-level reasoning. Apache 2.0 means you can ship it commercially without asking anyone's permission.*\n\n**Sources:** [Google Blog](https://blog.google/innovation-and-ai/technology/developers-tools/gemma-4/) | [Google DeepMind](https://deepmind.google/models/gemma/gemma-4/)\n\n---\n\n## 🏭 Maine Froze New Data Centers Until 2027. First US State to Do It.\n\nMaine passed legislation imposing a moratorium on new data centers requiring more than 20 megawatts of power, effective until October 2027 — the first US state to implement a broad pause on AI infrastructure.\n\n- **The trigger:** AI data center demand is straining New England's power grid. Maine relies on legacy hydro and Quebec imports — it lacks the infrastructure for a large data center complex.\n- **The irony:** The AI infrastructure boom is running headlong into physical constraints — land, water, electricity — that software cannot optimize away.\n\n*The AI revolution is discovering that atoms and electrons don't scale like tokens.*\n\n**Sources:** [Tech Startups](https://techstartups.com/2026/04/15/top-tech-news-today-april-15-2026/)\n\n---\n\n## ⚡ OpenAI Is Paying Cerebras $20B+ for AI Chips Over Three Years\n\nOpenAI struck a deal to buy servers powered by Cerebras' specialized AI chips for at least $20 billion over three years — potentially including an equity stake in Cerebras.\n\n- **The logic:** NVIDIA GPU supply is constrained. Cerebras makes wafer-scale chips optimized for AI inference. OpenAI is diversifying its hardware stack while possibly investing in a key supplier.\n- **The math:** $20B over three years from a company projecting $14B in annual losses. The chip bill alone exceeds OpenAI's current annual revenue.\n\n*OpenAI is spending $20B on chips to run the models that fund the chips. Circular economy.*\n\n**Sources:** [Dev Flokers](https://www.devflokers.com/blog/ai-news-last-24-hours-april-2026-model-releases-breakthroughs)"
  }
